---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'quick-decision', text: 'Quick Decision Guide', level: 2 },
  { id: 'requirements', text: 'Official Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Insurance', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Costs Breakdown', level: 2 },
  { id: 'timeline', text: 'Application Timeline', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'mistakes', text: 'Common Mistakes', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faq', text: 'FAQs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'verdict', text: 'Final Verdict', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { href: '/visas/digital-nomad-visa/in/spain', text: 'Spain Digital Nomad Visa' },
  { href: '/countries/spain/insurance', text: 'Spain Insurance Guide' },
  { href: '/visas/retirement-visa/in/spain', text: 'Spain Retirement Visa' },
  { href: '/best/expat-health-insurance', text: 'Best Expat Insurance' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Monthly Cost' },
  { key: 'bestFor', header: 'Best For' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', coverage: '€1M+ comprehensive', price: '€180-350', bestFor: 'Corporate transfers' },
  { provider: 'Sanitas', coverage: 'Full Spanish network', price: '€80-150', bestFor: 'Long-term residents' },
  { provider: 'Adeslas', coverage: 'Extensive local network', price: '€70-140', bestFor: 'Budget-conscious expats' },
  { provider: 'MAPFRE', coverage: 'National coverage', price: '€75-145', bestFor: 'Spanish integration' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Cost Item' },
  { key: 'amount', header: 'Amount' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'Work permit fee', amount: '€80', notes: 'Initial authorization' },
  { item: 'TIE card', amount: '€16-21', notes: 'Residence card issuance' },
  { item: 'NIE number', amount: '€12', notes: 'Tax identification' },
  { item: 'Health insurance', amount: '€70-350/month', notes: 'Required until Social Security' },
  { item: 'Apostille documents', amount: '€50-200', notes: 'Home country legalization' },
  { item: 'Translation costs', amount: '€100-300', notes: 'Sworn translations required' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Spain Work Permit 2026: Authorization, Social Security & Application Guide"
  headline="Spain Work Permit: Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  subheadline="Everything about working legally in Spain—permit types, Seguridad Social enrollment, and what insurance you need while building your Spanish career."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Health Insurance"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
>
  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section id="overview" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Spain Work Permit Overview</h2>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Quick Facts</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-primary-800">
        <li><strong>Permit Type:</strong> Autorización de residencia y trabajo (Work & Residence Authorization)</li>
        <li><strong>Initial Duration:</strong> 1 year (renewable to 2 years, then 5 years)</li>
        <li><strong>EU Blue Card Salary:</strong> €42,000/year minimum (1.5x average)</li>
        <li><strong>Processing Time:</strong> 2-4 months from outside Spain</li>
        <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Seguridad Social after employment registration</li>
        <li><strong>Path to PR:</strong> 5 years continuous legal residence</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 mb-4">
      Spain's work permit system requires employer sponsorship, with the company initiating the process before you can apply for your visa. Once employed, you're automatically enrolled in Spain's comprehensive Social Security system (Seguridad Social), which provides public healthcare, pension contributions, and unemployment benefits.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 mb-4">
      The Spanish labor market has opened significantly to non-EU workers, particularly in tech, healthcare, and hospitality sectors. Barcelona and Madrid host thriving startup ecosystems, while coastal regions need hospitality professionals. The process involves both the Extranjería (immigration) and your employer's Social Security registration.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700">
      Understanding which permit category fits your situation—general work authorization, EU Blue Card for highly skilled workers, or intra-company transfer—determines both the requirements and timeline for your Spanish work adventure.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Spain Work Permit is Right For You If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ You have a job offer from a Spanish employer</li>
          <li>✓ Your profession is in demand (tech, healthcare, hospitality)</li>
          <li>✓ You want comprehensive EU-style social benefits</li>
          <li>✓ You value work-life balance and quality of life</li>
          <li>✓ You're open to learning Spanish for integration</li>
          <li>✓ You want eventual EU permanent residence</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Consider Alternatives If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• You don't have an employer sponsor lined up</li>
          <li>• Your profession isn't in high demand</li>
          <li>• You need faster processing (try Portugal or Netherlands)</li>
          <li>• You prefer lower tax rates (consider UAE or Singapore)</li>
          <li>• Bureaucracy frustrates you easily</li>
          <li>• You're self-employed (Digital Nomad Visa may fit better)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Official Requirements -->
  <section id="requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Official Requirements</h2>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Eligibility Criteria</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
      <li><strong>Job offer:</strong> From a registered Spanish company willing to sponsor</li>
      <li><strong>Labor market test:</strong> Employer proves no suitable EU candidate available</li>
      <li><strong>Qualifications:</strong> Relevant credentials for the position</li>
      <li><strong>Clean record:</strong> No criminal history in past 5 years</li>
      <li><strong>Health certificate:</strong> Medical clearance from approved doctor</li>
      <li><strong>EU Blue Card:</strong> €42,000+ salary for highly skilled positions</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Required Documents</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
      <li>Valid passport (minimum 1 year validity)</li>
      <li>National visa application form (completed in Spanish)</li>
      <li>Employment contract or job offer letter</li>
      <li>Company registration documents (employer provides)</li>
      <li>Professional qualifications (apostilled and translated)</li>
      <li>Criminal background check (apostilled)</li>
      <li>Medical certificate</li>
      <li>Proof of accommodation in Spain</li>
      <li>Passport-size photos (white background)</li>
      <li>Private health insurance certificate (initial period)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Permit Categories</h3>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-neutral-700">
        <li><strong>General Work Authorization:</strong> Standard employer-sponsored permit, requires labor market test</li>
        <li><strong>EU Blue Card:</strong> For highly skilled workers earning €42,000+, simplified processing</li>
        <li><strong>Intra-Company Transfer (ICT):</strong> Multinational company transfers, no labor test needed</li>
        <li><strong>Highly Qualified Professional:</strong> Management or technical specialists, streamlined process</li>
        <li><strong>Shortage Occupation:</strong> Professions on Spain's shortage list, expedited processing</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Initial Insurance Requirement</h3>
      <p class="text-blue-800 mb-3">
        Private health insurance with no co-pays or coverage gaps is required for your visa application. Once your TIE card is issued and you're registered with Social Security through employment, you gain access to the public Sistema Nacional de Salud (SNS).
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
        <li><strong>Visa application:</strong> Full private coverage required</li>
        <li><strong>After employment:</strong> Seguridad Social provides public healthcare</li>
        <li><strong>Minimum coverage:</strong> €30,000+ for medical expenses</li>
        <li><strong>No exclusions:</strong> Must cover pre-existing conditions</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Why Many Choose to Keep Private Insurance</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
      While Seguridad Social provides comprehensive coverage, many expat workers maintain supplementary private insurance for faster access to specialists, English-speaking doctors, and private hospital options. Spanish public healthcare is excellent but can involve waiting times for non-urgent care.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Public Healthcare (SNS)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-neutral-600 text-sm">
          <li>• Free after Social Security registration</li>
          <li>• Comprehensive hospital coverage</li>
          <li>• Low prescription costs (€4.24 cap for workers)</li>
          <li>• Longer wait times for specialists</li>
          <li>• Spanish-language consultations typical</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Private Insurance Benefits</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-1 text-neutral-600 text-sm">
          <li>• Same-day or next-day specialist appointments</li>
          <li>• English-speaking medical staff</li>
          <li>• Private hospital room options</li>
          <li>• Dental and optical coverage available</li>
          <li>• International coverage for travel</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recommended Providers -->
  <section id="recommended-providers" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
      <p class="text-neutral-700">
        <strong>Cigna Global</strong> suits corporate transferees and those wanting international-standard coverage with English support. Higher cost but seamless experience for those unfamiliar with Spanish healthcare navigation.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">
        <strong>Sanitas</strong> (owned by Bupa) offers the strongest private network in Spain with over 40,000 professionals. Excellent for long-term residents who want Spanish-integrated coverage with international backup.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">
        <strong>Adeslas</strong> provides excellent value with extensive coverage at competitive prices. Popular among Spanish locals and expats alike, with good English support in major cities.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">
        <strong>MAPFRE</strong> is Spain's largest insurer, offering comprehensive packages that can include home and car insurance bundles. Good for those planning to fully integrate into Spanish life.
      </p>
    </div>

    <CTABox
      title="Compare Spain Health Insurance Options"
      description="Find the right coverage for your work permit application and ongoing needs in Spain."
      buttonText="Compare Plans"
      buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    />
  </section>

  <!-- Costs Breakdown -->
  <section id="costs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Costs Breakdown</h2>

    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Total Estimated Setup Costs</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
        <li><strong>Administrative fees:</strong> €110-115 (permits and NIE)</li>
        <li><strong>Document preparation:</strong> €150-500 (apostilles and translations)</li>
        <li><strong>Initial insurance:</strong> €210-1,050 (3 months coverage)</li>
        <li><strong>Total initial outlay:</strong> €470-1,665</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-4">
        Note: Many employers cover visa fees and initial relocation costs as part of the hiring package. Clarify what's included before accepting an offer.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-4">Ongoing Monthly Costs in Spain</h3>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
        <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€1,200-2,500</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Madrid rent (1-bed)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
        <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€800-1,800</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Barcelona rent (1-bed)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
        <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€600-1,200</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Valencia/Seville rent</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Application Timeline -->
  <section id="timeline" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Application Timeline</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Weeks 1-2</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Secure Job Offer</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Accept position and sign preliminary contract. Employer begins preparing sponsorship documents and labor market test (if required).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Weeks 3-6</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Employer Submits Authorization Request</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Your employer files with the Unidad de Grandes Empresas (large companies) or provincial Extranjería office. This is the longest wait—typically 4-8 weeks for approval.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Week 7-8</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Prepare Personal Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">While waiting for employer authorization, gather personal documents: criminal background check, medical certificate, academic credentials. Get apostilles and sworn translations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Week 9</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Apply for Work Visa at Consulate</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Once employer authorization is granted, apply for your visa at the Spanish consulate in your home country. Bring all documents and proof of private health insurance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Weeks 10-12</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Visa Processing</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Consulate processes your visa application. Standard processing takes 2-4 weeks. EU Blue Card applications may be faster.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Week 13</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4 pb-6">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Arrive and Start Work</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Enter Spain with your work visa. Your employer registers you with Social Security. Within 30 days, apply for your TIE (Tarjeta de Identidad de Extranjero) residence card.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-24 text-sm font-medium text-primary-600">Week 14-16</div>
        <div class="flex-grow border-l-2 border-primary-200 pl-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold">Complete Registration</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Receive NIE number, register at local padron (census), and obtain your TIE card. Once registered with Social Security, you can access public healthcare.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Real-World Scenarios -->
  <section id="scenarios" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Tech Worker from US to Barcelona</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Senior developer with €55,000 salary offer from a Spanish startup.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Outcome: EU Blue Card approved in 10 weeks. Fast-track processing due to salary threshold. Public healthcare plus Sanitas private for convenience.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Healthcare Professional from Philippines</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Nurse with job offer from Madrid hospital.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Outcome: Shortage occupation list enabled expedited processing. Required Spanish nursing credential homologation. Full SNS coverage as healthcare worker.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Hospitality Manager from UK</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Hotel manager position in Costa del Sol, €32,000 salary.</p>
        <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">Outcome: Post-Brexit now requires work permit like non-EU nationals. Standard processing took 14 weeks. Chose Adeslas for private coverage in tourist area.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Engineer with Family from India</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Automotive engineer, spouse and two children accompanying.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Outcome: Family visas processed together. All enrolled in Social Security as dependents. Chose MAPFRE family plan for supplementary coverage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Marketing Coordinator from Brazil</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Entry-level position, €24,000 salary, employer new to sponsorship.</p>
        <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">Outcome: Labor market test required 6 additional weeks. Employer made errors on first submission. Total timeline: 18 weeks. Used budget Adeslas plan.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Corporate Transfer from Japan</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm mb-2">Intra-company transfer to Spanish subsidiary for 3 years.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Outcome: ICT permit avoided labor market test. Company handled all paperwork. International Cigna policy continued from Japanese coverage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-400 p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Starting Work Before TIE Card</h4>
        <p class="text-red-800">Your work visa allows entry, but you must be registered with Social Security before legally starting work. Some employers try to start you "unofficially" before paperwork completes—this can jeopardize your permit and their ability to sponsor.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-400 p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Insurance With Coverage Gaps</h4>
        <p class="text-red-800">Spanish consulates reject insurance policies with co-payments, deductibles over €3,000, or pre-existing condition exclusions. "Travel insurance" is not sufficient—you need proper health insurance meeting Spanish requirements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-400 p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Missing the 30-Day TIE Window</h4>
        <p class="text-red-800">You must apply for your TIE card within 30 days of arriving in Spain. Missing this deadline can result in fines and complications with your residency status. Book your cita previa (appointment) immediately upon arrival—slots fill fast.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-400 p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Untranslated or Non-Apostilled Documents</h4>
        <p class="text-red-800">All foreign documents need apostilles from the issuing country AND sworn translations by a certified Spanish translator. DIY translations are rejected. Start this process early—apostilles can take weeks in some countries.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-400 p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Not Registering at Padrón</h4>
        <p class="text-red-800">The padrón (municipal census) registration is required for healthcare access, school enrollment for children, and many official processes. Register at your local town hall within the first month. You'll need your rental contract or proof of address.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Healthcare System -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Spanish Healthcare System for Workers</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 mb-6">
      Spain's public healthcare system (Sistema Nacional de Salud or SNS) ranks among Europe's best, providing comprehensive coverage to all legal residents registered with Social Security. Once you're employed and registered, you and your dependents receive a tarjeta sanitaria (health card) for free public healthcare access.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Public Healthcare Works</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600 text-sm">
          <li><strong>Primary care:</strong> Assigned a Centro de Salud and GP near your home</li>
          <li><strong>Specialists:</strong> GP referral required, may involve waiting lists</li>
          <li><strong>Hospitals:</strong> Full coverage at public hospitals</li>
          <li><strong>Emergencies:</strong> 24/7 at any hospital, no prior authorization</li>
          <li><strong>Prescriptions:</strong> Workers pay 40% (capped at €4.24/item)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's Covered</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600 text-sm">
          <li>✓ All GP and specialist consultations</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital stays and surgery</li>
          <li>✓ Emergency care</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health services</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care (excellent coverage)</li>
          <li>✗ Dental (emergency only)</li>
          <li>✗ Optical (not covered)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Regional Healthcare Variations</h4>
      <p class="text-primary-800">
        Healthcare in Spain is managed by autonomous communities, meaning coverage quality and wait times vary by region. Catalonia, Madrid, and the Basque Country generally have the shortest waits and most extensive services. Smaller regions may have longer specialist waits. If healthcare access is a priority, factor this into your location decision.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQs -->
  <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on my work permit?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">During the first year, you're tied to your sponsoring employer and region. After renewal (year 2+), you can work for any employer in any region without new authorization. Always notify immigration of employer changes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I lose my job?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You receive unemployment benefits (paro) based on your contribution period—from 4 to 24 months of payments. Your residence permit remains valid, but you must find new employment before renewal or change to job-seeker status.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Spouse and children under 21 can apply for family reunification visas once you have your residence permit. They're automatically covered by your Social Security enrollment as dependents.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need Spanish skills?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Not for the visa, but essential for daily life and career advancement. Many tech companies in Barcelona and Madrid operate in English, but government offices, healthcare, and most workplaces use Spanish.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path to permanent residence?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After 5 years of continuous legal residence (not more than 6 months outside Spain per year), you can apply for long-term EU residence. After 10 years, you're eligible for Spanish citizenship.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-5">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is private insurance worth it if I have Social Security?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Depends on your priorities. Public healthcare is excellent for serious conditions but can have 2-4 month waits for specialists. Private insurance (€70-150/month) provides same-week appointments and English-speaking doctors.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Final Verdict</h2>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <p class="text-lg text-primary-900 mb-4">
        <strong>Spain offers an unbeatable combination of quality of life, comprehensive social benefits, and path to EU citizenship—if you can navigate the bureaucracy.</strong>
      </p>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The Spanish work permit process requires patience and employer commitment. Processing times of 3-4 months are normal, and the system heavily favors those with skills in shortage occupations or meeting EU Blue Card salary thresholds. Once established, however, you gain access to one of Europe's best healthcare systems, strong labor protections, and a lifestyle that prioritizes work-life balance.
      </p>
      <p class="text-primary-800">
        For the visa application, you'll need comprehensive private health insurance without coverage gaps. After employment registration, Seguridad Social covers your healthcare needs, but many expats maintain private coverage for faster access and English-speaking services. Spanish insurers like Sanitas and Adeslas offer excellent value compared to international providers.
      </p>
